guage (DGS). Naturalistic dialogues from the DGS Corpus form the primary data source. It is shown that certain semantic properties, also known to govern transitivity marking in spoken languages, are predictive of verb type in DGS, where systematic iconic mappings play a mediating role. The results enable the formulation of cross-linguistic predictions about the interplay between verb semantics and verb type in sign languages. An analysis of the morphosyntactic properties of different verb types leads up to the conclusion that even ‘plain’ verbs agree with their arguments, where iconicity again plays a crucial role.The findings motivate a unified syntactic analysis in terms of agreement of constructions with verbs of all types, thus offering a novel solution to the typological puzzle that supposedly only a subset of verbs agree in DGS and other sign languages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 4aDGS. 4aDeutsche Gebärdensprache (DGS). 4aDeutsche Gebärdensprache. 4aIkonizität. 4aKongruenz. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Sign Language.2bisacsh  aGerman Sign Language.  aIconicity.  aVerb Agreement.0 cEPUBz97831107428480 cprintz978311074274940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311074278740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110742787423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110742787/original  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK